flowRoot.flowPara: Digital voting technologies must use cryptographic constructions such as homomorphic encryption, ring signatures, or zero-knowledge proofs to ensure tally integrity and voters privacy. We focus on cryptographic constructions which are shown provably secure under computational assumptions. We claim that these proofs must be completely formalized using computer proof assistants which rely on sound theoretical foundations. Type theory provides such foundations. Agda is a modern
language, system and tool for such theory.
The construction shown here is one of the state-of-the-art voting system
called Prêt-à-Voter. In particular, the proof illustrated here is the reduction
between the privacy property of Prêt-à-Voter (called Receipt-Freeness), down to a variation of the semantic security for the underlying encryption scheme (called IND-CCA2†).
Our proof is inspired from “Proving Prêt-à-Voter Receipt Free using
Computational Security Models” by D. Khader, P. Ryan, and Q. Tang. We had to provide the lacking details, to fix some parts, finally we managed to also simplify the proof.
Our work is still “in-progress” as we aim at stronger results and a more in depth coverage of the various sub-constructions needed.
Cryptographic constructions using Computational Security Models, constructively proven within the Type Theory of Agda − N. Pouillard, D. Gustafsson, and C. Schürmann
